<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-158-664  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 158 664.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computing Canada  Feb 16 1989 v15 n4 p34(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Choosing a mainframe 4GL for SAA. (fourth-generation language,Systems Application Architecture)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Richter, Chris.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>There are several types of fourth-generation languages (4GLs), andthey have a broad range of functions and prices.andP;  Users who wantto stick with IBM should choose a 4GL that is compatible withSystems Application Architecture (SAA).andP;  The main categories of4GLs are: information management systems, application development,and database management.andP;  Application development 4GLs aregenerally more expensive than the others, but they are becomingincreasingly critical to business.andP;  Information management systemsare the least expensive and are usually used for informationretrieval, updating, and report generating.andP;  Database management4GLs, such as Relational Technology's Ingres and Oracle Corp'sOracle, are proprietary databases that have their own 4GL.andP;  One ofthe biggest drawbacks to most 4GLs is the lack of true StructuredQuery Language (SQL) support, which will be needed once SAAbecomes entrenched.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Mainframe ComputersSAACompatibilityStructured Query LanguageSoftware SelectionData Base Management SystemsProgram Development ToolsFourth-Generation Languages.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>